text: in the midst of our national conversation about sexual assault surrounding dr. christine blasey ford and supreme court nominee brett kavanaugh, i was honored earlier today to be a guest on “on second thought” with host virginia prescott. alongside sally sheppard, the executive director of the cottage, a sexual assault and children’s advocacy center in athens, ga, we discussed topics including the psychological effects of sexual assault (e.g., repressed memories, ptsd, triggers), why women might choose to not report or disclose that they’ve been sexually assaulted, and the role of psychologists and advocates in healing from trauma. join in on the conversation by downloading today’s episode of “on second thought” on npr, apple music, or wherever you get your podcasts. http://wjsp.drupal.publicbroadcasting.net/post/second-thought-monday-october-1-2018 #advocacy #academia #research #blackdoctors #metoo #stopkavanaugh #believesurvivors #activism #theempowerlab

text:
in 1970 my grandma kidnapped my dad and his three sisters. they were on the run for 7 years, changing names, evading the law...disappearing. 
after the children had grown and the dust had settled, after i was born, she wrote her story. it sat on a shelf for many years...until i, her eldest grandchild, offered to share it.
.
i know snippets of stories. i know the general timeline. i know in each of my dad's school yearbooks he has a different last name- and i know where to look for his pictures.
.
but, this is my first time reading the entire tale. in order to digest the details myself, i am reading one chapter each week, aloud, without editing or editorializing. i shall learn the details in real time...with you.
“my grandma: wanted by the fbi”
.
i'm editing her book as i go. i find learning this family story from her perspective fascinating. i hope you do too. (link in bio)
.
.
.

text: ~~~spreadinglovespreadinglight~~~ be authentic: ”face the world as fabulous you” by clarity~~~ “when a new day begins, dare to smile gratefully. when there is darkness, dare to be the first to shine a light. when there is injustice, dare to be the first to condemn it. when something seems difficult, dare to do it anyway.”-steve maraboli~~~ how often have we stopped ourselves from going after our dreams; from releasing our inherent fabulousness? many of us are slaves to days of the yesteryears, holding on to long lists of what-i-did-back-in-the days. when life becomes too challenging or overly complex, we simply switch the screens of our lives to fall back to familiar ways of being. believe me---i am often sitting in the front seat of that bullet train. therefore, i find it easy to relay these familiar feelings. however, in this new iteration of my life, where i have decided to live authentically and to be fabulous while doing it, my question is why not? why should we put aside our most ardent dreams and goals to settle for lesser than? just be fabulous my friends!~~~#deepthoughts #fabulous #befabulous #survivor #metoo #metoomovement #pushthrough #live #liveyourlife #now #clarity #awareness #presence #writersofinstagram #writer #blogger #communicate #artistsoninstagram #arttherapy #healingart #enjoylife #lifeisbeautiful #livenow #yoga #yogacommunity #now #here =#woke #personalgrowth #reclaim🙏🏽for likes and follows❤️✨✨❤️💫

to teach him how to treat himself + others with respect, how to have a healthy view towards sex, and how to be a man in this “boys will be boys” society.🙅🏼‍♀️
.
i’m raising a man. a man who will not only only open the door, cook and clean, work hard to take care of himself and his family... 💛
.
but most importantly, i’m gently raising a man who will understand how to communicate his emotions without being abusive. to understand boundaries and especially the word “no”. 👊🏼
.
also... to feel empathy and understand that it’s okay to cry when he’s sad. to understand that he can be strong and sensitive and passionate. and to know that he can be a great man and show nothing but love to everyone in his life, especially his future partner, in this world of low expectations for men. 👦🏼
.
thank you @thebluegrassmom for inspiring me to write this post 💛
📷 @brdypps

the "women's movement" has been swept into the mainstream and become more diverse, and social media has become increasingly effective at mobilizing younger generations of women and girls - @cnn

it's time to fight back ladies! stand up, show up, share your story and lets make history!
. .
. .
thank you @her.summit

text:
siempre mostramos los mejores momentos, la mejor foto, el mejor filtro. nadie muestra cuando llora, cuando tiene un mal día, cuando hay tristeza; sufrimos en silencio. “¿sabes qué se siente📽?” es un cortometraje que grabé hace unos meses, en el que tuve que ponerme en los zapatos de una mujer maltratada, física y emocionalmente, con un miedo inmenso a decir “no estoy bien" y una necesidad de esconder su dolor. 
se vale estar triste, ¿no creen? hace parte de lo que somos... si hoy tú lo estás: 
respira... acepta... llora... suelta... los momentos que más nos desestabilizan  siempre traen nuevos comienzos. ❤

text: due process is not some willy-nilly preference like choosing which candy bar you enjoy. it’s to prevent kings from killing you in your sleep, from secret police throwing you in a siberian prison camp. it is built on the notion that reality exists and not merely a construct of political gamesmanship. if you truly harm, you should truly meet justice. if you truly did not, you should be protected and defended by every last member of society. you are protected as innocent until the evidence of reality exposes you. this is your sacred duty as a human, to humanize others. otherwise you will destroy people, including yourself, and be judged by the same measure. you reap what you sow. this is why the 2nd amendment is so important. you have power until you forfeit it. you are trusted and innocent until you commit crimes. you shall not be infringed as a citizen.#confirmkavanaugh #scotus #4a #dueprocess #midterms #redwave #bluewave #metoo #ibelievehim #democrat #republican #2a

text:
i'm still discovering how my sexual abuse trauma affected me. one eye-opener for me is how it affected my relationship with others.

my victim mindset:
•self-centeredness= woe is me, i didn’t deserve this. i don’t deserve this. i deserve to be treated better.
•fearful= untrusting. reject others.
•shame= insecurity. avoid others.
•anger/bitterness= mean, harsh, unkind.
•unforgiveness =quick to write others off.
•vengeful= quick to punish others. not merciful.
•prideful =think less of others. overly critical of others. blame others. avoid others.

i was sinned against, yet my reaction and behavior was sinful as well. ironically, not against my abuser, but against others. but more importantly against the lord.
•
praise god for the truth of god’s word, for helping me overcome my victim mentality and allowing me to foster meaningful and loving relationships.
•
“and you will know the truth, and the truth will make you free."” john‬ ‭8:32‬

•
•
•
•

yet, i was left without a shield.~

text:
a tea blend for coping with the current news cycle as a sexual abuse survivor:
🌱lemon balm for calming & anti-anxiety
🌹rose for emotional healing
🌱lavender for peace & happiness
✨borage for courage and anti-stress
.
.
.
i returned home from a blissful weekend of camping, with no technology, in one of my favorite places, the eastern sierras. but sadly, after returning home and checking the inter webs, i was rushed with anxiety, triggered by the current events and perpetuated on social media.
.
i wanted to share with you with this tea blend that was shared in one of my herbal groups. and also these reminders:
survivors don’t owe the world their stories of survival.
turning away or hiding from triggering headlines, people, or stories isn’t selfish, it’s selfcare.

text:
i had a different caption in mind for this picture but i have something on my mind. i was followed most of the way home, i'm not sure how long this man was behind me, but he started yelling at me until i took off my headphones. he asked if i wanted to make money taking pictures for him. and then he watched me walk away and i was just grateful he didn't follow me farther. this is the second incident this week where i've had headphones on. this is the 5th time this week a man has made me uncomfortable. with what's going on nationally, i'm angry at men and i don't want to be. dudes, be better, i'm begging you. be safe out there everyone. 
that being said my life is beautiful, this is a small aspect. i am grateful for the hugs the babes gave me when i got home 💕
#feminism #respectwomen #ibelieveher #metoo #divinefeminine #dobettermen

text: 7:51pm i went over a year without being able to be randomly touched. i felt like i was dying. and i felt so alone, but i couldnt. i would watch people around me touch so casually and tears would just fall bc i wanted to be touched so badly, but i honestly couldnt deal. friends would get angry and tell me how fucked up it was not to allow them to care for me, and i would cry. bc i couldnt explain to them in words that every hug...every simple touch was so wrenching. i cringed any time even my mom tried to wrap her arms around me. every random unexpected touch felt like a complete violation. and i acted like it. i knew in my heart they werent, but i couldnt hide how my body felt, you know? then there was intimacy. i had to tell myself repeatedly “youre safe. youre safe.” and to this day and beyond i’ll ask, “may i trust you? am i safe with you?” outloud. to anyone wanting to be close to me. and not even just in reference to a physical touch. even eye contact conversations required the same ask. friends...family...mama...anyone could get the drama. lol. things have a way of changing you. forever. but im learning to appreciate the healing in humans and ask for the one thing ive always loved and can never get enough of: hugs. “failure to thrive” is a thing w babies and children. it deals w a babys lack of development due to lack of human contact. literally! adults are no different. we need each other. for basic survival. remember that the next time “you dont need nobody” or you set up to hurt somebody else. we need each other out here. every human needs the touch of another human. even if its just on their hand...their shoulder...something basic. then there are aliens like me: we need even more🙏🏽. sending a hug to anyone that needs one today❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️. more love🖤. #artandloveonly #morelove #houseofleaders #hugging #hugs #goodmedicine #askfirst #lol #but #yeah #hugsareeverything #thehealing #writeyourstory #changethenarrative #changetheworld operationconsent #metoo #webelieveyou #doyoubelieveme

text:
why i didn’t report it. 
this post contains very sensitive & personal information. i debated with myself back & forth for months before deciding to finally share it. i decided to share it with those who choose to read this in hopes of helping someone else struggling with similar battles just like christine blasey ford did just recently shared with the entire world. 
on april 22, 2017, i attended a bachelorette party in chicago & we went to a male strip club. this was my first & only time going to a male strip club. i didn’t really know exactly what to expect as i had only been to strips clubs with female strippers. i remember there were 3 men who tried to get me to have leave with them, but i had no interest. the first one wanted money. the second one asked if i’d like to go out back to his car with him. i politely declined & told him i had a boyfriend & he respectfully left me alone the rest of the evening. the third, however, succeeded against my will. 
i had been drinking all evening & was feeling it when a man who had danced by us in the vip earlier approached me & my friend. i remember he had an accent & was black. he made it very clear he wanted to have sex with me. my friend kept whispering in my ear that we should have a threesome with him & that she found him super attractive. i shoved it off & said it’s not my thing & i was happy in my current relationship. they continued to pressure me but i left them to dance with the other girls. my friend wanted some fresh air & i didn’t want her to go alone so i went with but so did he. i remember sitting on the sidewalk as people walked by & taxis parked out front dropping off k picking up. she said she wanted to leave & got up to get a taxi. i told her it wasn’t a good idea because the other girls wouldn’t know where we were. she persisted & he said he could give us a ride. without even thinking my friend said accepted his offer. she was going to go regardless of me going so i had to go to keep her safe. we got to his car & she pointed out that he drove a bmw as if i cared. the entire ride there he had his hand on my leg & kept sliding it higher & higher. i put my hand on the edge of my romper to keep

text:
>> coming to you from the lake << my heart is so full, lately , however i’m
coming to one of those silent happy moments constantly where i can’t even begin to put words to these feelings . 
i’ve been to 11 d consciousness and mostly in my earth body i am in a state of christ consciousness. 
what i’m learning , is love all parts of yourself , find the parts of others you can have compassion for through understanding, i am learning how amazing it feels to love and forgive without bulldozing the parts of you still in pain. i am learning to constantly sit with the resistance and i am learning to be brave and vulnerable. 
i am coming more to the shadow awareness of my deep social anxiety lately which came about form serious enmeshment trauma and other traumas . 
i am learning that this part of me is okay as she is, and i’m working with her shyness instead of against her. 
i’ve always had social anxiety its this massive tightness that comes over me when the cues to let someone into my fortress are being called that i feel this rigorously in my entire body. 
i used to have friends who would hurt me and by both parties responsibility that were toxic . 
this year on my birthday, a friend of mine reached out who i hold very dear to my heart and the vibration that she wasn’t good for me stuck out like a sore thumb. i’ve walked away from many friendships, and also a few relationships in the past five years that weren’t serving me . 
i made the decision to completely cut off all contact with my moms foster family, this year that includes the massive decision to say no to two weddings my cousins were getting married . 
this decision came abruptly from hearing #metoo stories about this “family” i had grown up with. 
i can also trace social trauma to the memories of being at the cottage my foster family owns with my 15 cousins . 
they were my first earth play ground and i was shunned from the get go, especially from the female cousins who i intuitively came to a realization that they felt threatened i would become one of the “favourites” which was from the strong energy of competition in this household . 
these decisions that i’ve made are huge however no parts of

text:
finding the positive in a negative situation is how i cope with shitty things happening. i have found myself having a pretty tough time navigating the internet lately with all off the post that are happening. i have seen posts ranging from support to outrage, from jokes at the expense of survivors to positive powerful messages to survivors. it has been almost a year since the #metoo movement began and i have to say that there has been some impressive steps taken from humans to make this world a better place. i am thankful for that. the flip to that is that there has also been a lot of people publicly saying ignorant and hurtful things, which i am also thankful for. it makes taking out the figurative trash that much easier. 
1. survivors and or women, how have things over the last year improved for you since #metoo began?
2. allies, how have you personally changed and what kind of steps have you taken in your day to day to end rape culture and/or toxic masculinity? 
i am sure that i am not alone in the world of survivors feeling the emotions of past sexual assaults right now. i am sorry that this is something we have to go through to move forward and see change. we are strong and resilient, we have survived yesterday and the day before, and the day before that. we can keep going and we have to. there are survivors that need us to be strong for them when they cannot be, there will be days when they will be strong for us when we cannot. this fight doesn't seem to be getting any easier.

i have had countless conversations, discussions and admittedly a few arguments with people over the topics of rape/assault and rape culture. i have watched videos and read stories. i have cried listening to survivors. i have marched. i have written emails to my government. i have gotten out of bed when i didn't think it was possible. i have masked my own pain with less than ideal coping mechanisms. i have dove into my own recovery with positive tools. days where the patriarchy has crushed me, days where i have smashed it. 
please tell me all this work we have been putting in over our lifetime is not without something positive coming from it. 
i.am.getting.tired.

text:
i went to see my wonderful naturopathic doctor today. we have communicated via instagram so i feel like i have seen her but i kind of fell off of my own self care for a while. it had been years since i was in 🤪
.
now i usually live a fairly clean lifestyle but i am also a woman of extremes. i am on plan or i am fucking off plan. can you tell which one it has been of late?
.
i also have done a lot of internal work in the past 5 years and while i have grown so much. i sometimes struggle with depression and anxiety even still. .
i have also been in an abusive relationship.  and i think at times,  it is like peeling an onion. you get through more and more layers each time you explore.
. 
i was recently accused of having a vendetta against my ex. and i suppose if wanting him to help support his kids is a vendetta...ya, i have one. i had warned my boyfriend that when he found out about him,  the games would begin....the first one was cutting off child support,  the second was fucking with his teensy tiny parenting time. the power games are fun!!
.
and it got me down. real down. i did reiki. i told myself to get my head out of my ass and i told myself to be gentle with myself. that i was dealing with a lot. i started having crazy dreams. and my procrastination game got stronger. snooze was pressed more often. .
but today, i feel better as i told dr. andrea about all my new fun symptoms and how clearly my body was/is screaming at me.  i even told her what things i knew that i needed to change but couldn't or wouldn't. i told her how angry i have been and impatient with #mywhy and even the fun hail mary parenting attempt from yesterday. .
the fantastic news is that i am not crazy. but my stress load has become a bit too much to bear and my system is saying nope.....we need more support. unfortunately or fortunately, i am strong and push through for way too fucking long. i told #myguy yesterday that i didn't have the fight in me to deal with my ex. but something tells me that dr. andrea will get the zing in my step, my qi moving again and me back. .
her prescription also included me writing. so you may see a bit more of my rants 😊

text:
did i just post this? 😱 i did.
a lot of us, not all but a lot of us are a wicked, conniving bunch.  and if backed into a corner and caught in a lie, we will stop at nothing and destroy anyone to keep our secret safe and our lie in tact.  this is why, throughout my entire life, as far back as grade school, my closest and dearest friends have always been boys/men – jealousy and envy are toxic.  they cause pain and they can destroy lives – and women have mastered both.
i think many of us have it all wrong.  being born a woman does not give us a lifetime pass to lie.  being born a woman does not make us the more credible of the sexes: “it must be true because a woman said it was!” and because i’m a woman, i must always stand with and side with women, truth be damned!  right?  wrong!  that fucked up ideology is complete and utter bullshit.  and that is exactly what is wrong with this feminist driven #metoo movement.  it’s pure poison.  and it’s frighteningly dangerous for our men.  no, i stand on the side of truth.  gender does not predicate with whom my loyalty lies.  my loyalty lies on the side of truth.
i’m quite certain this post will not go over well with some and that’s ok.  unfollow and carry on.  most of you know i could give two shits about others’ opinions of me.  i post whatever it is that i’m passionate about.  and watching the left’s carefully orchestrated take down of an honorable and decent man, with the media circus playing right along;  watching the decimation of a man’s life, his family and esteemed career has me angrier than i’ve been in a very long time.  this liberal freak show pains me – my heart breaks for judge kavanaugh and his family.  i can’t even begin to imagine the hell they are suffering through.  but what brings me the most pain is knowing the majority of those peddling these grotesque lies are women.  and that i’m not surprised.  i expected no less from my “sisters.” that is what hurts the most.💔
.
.
.
.
#stopthisinsanity #confirmkavanaugh #istandwithbrett

text:
myth: rape does not happen that often.

fact: it was estimated in 2017 that 321,500 people were victims of rape and sexual assault. 
a lot of assaults go unreported, but the bureau of justice statistics does an annual household survey that captures data on crimes like rape and sexual assault. these reports help us understand who these victims are and how they respond to being attacked.
everyone handles the trauma of being assaulted differently, so it’s important for us to listen and learn how we can be a part of someone’s healing process.

text:
washington — in the days leading up to a public allegation that supreme court nominee brett kavanaugh exposed himself to a college classmate, the judge and his team were communicating behind the scenes with friends to refute the claim, according to text messages obtained by nbc news.

kerry berchem, who was at yale with both kavanaugh and his accuser, deborah ramirez, has tried to get those messages to the fbi for its newly reopened investigation into the matter but says she has yet to be contacted by the bureau.

the texts between berchem and karen yarasavage, both friends of kavanaugh, suggest that the nominee was personally talking with former classmates about ramirez’s story in advance of the new yorker article that made her allegation public. in one message, yarasavage said kavanaugh asked her to go on the record in his defense. two other messages show communication between kavanaugh's team and former classmates in advance of the story.

the texts also demonstrate that kavanaugh and ramirez were more socially connected than previously understood and that ramirez was uncomfortable around kavanaugh when they saw each other at a wedding 10 years after they graduated. berchem's efforts also show that some potential witnesses have been unable to get important information to the fbi.

text:
my beautiful sisters,
i have a gift for your body and your energetic and emotional bodies today.
.
if you are feeling feelings between sadness and rage around #metoo and the generational mistreating of women, this sweet and soft yoga practice is for you.
.
this 38 minute yoga practice is slow and focuses solely on the inner thighs and inner groins. using 2 blocks and one strap, we drop in deeply with a saturated attention.
.
we start seated with massage and emotional release invitations before we come standing for a few standing poses such as a manually assisted wide squat and modified parsvakonasana. additional poses include upavista konasana, supta baddha konasana and legs up the wall pose with a middle split.
.
the theme weaves in elements of our female essence, invites us to grant ourselves the permission to open and to reclaim our body as ours. yummmm.
.
i love you.
i love that we are women on a mission to love ourselves more deeply.
i love that we can support one another is overcoming and rising up.
i love that there is a potential inside of us that is beyond what words could express.
.
for everything inside of you that is hurting right now, i am sending love. love and light.
.
i have put this video on a password for you to receive it for the next week. i hope it serves your heart, soul, body and being.
.
i love you.
.
https://vimeo.com/120268815/
password:
ibelongtome
.
xo
samantha fox olson
p.s. please feel free to share this post, tag a sister. additionally, you could simply share the link and password to them too.
.
i will only have it set on password for a week so that i can get it back on my online training site so please make the space for this soon. it's for you.

text:
this last week, i've been having so many conversations with humxn beloveds irl and here in ig land and i couldn't be more grateful for all the spaces held with such ferocious tenderness.
•
all the precious convos, all the thoughtful processing, all the complex emotions. my #ragevolcano is transmuting into an appreciation volcano.* and look, while i'm still deeply angry, i'm so clear that we're powerful and our power is growing.
•
to keep cultivating your power (cuz the world needs it) listen to the needs of your emotional body. tend to your insides so your outside will reflect your ideals.
•
if all you can do today is breathe, that's ok my love.
•
keep learning to stand in your healthy middle. most of us overextend. we're taught to. i feel that dr. ford showed us that while she was pressing her edge by coming forward, she was also declaring that she would no longer stand to privately emotionally and psychically labor for someone else's violent crimes.
•
we're in a collective healing time now. you can learn to let people rise to meet you. it takes trust, which takes time. trust, power, healing -- they're all practices.
•
in my bio is an exercise i've shared over the years** to help you see where you might be overextending in your relationships and how to find your alignment. (you may be prompted to request permission to view... go ahead and i'll confirm you asap! exercise starts at ~3:40 in.)
•
as much as we're in a time of justice (the justice card and the high priestess card are our 2018 cards in traditional tarot -- makes so much sense, right??), we're in a time of dignity and refinement (my word of the year). a time when our internal and our external must be in alignment. a time for our deepest values to be reflected in our actions.
•
we're continuing to dig deep in the unearthing of our traumas. there's a collective transmuting of the pain and suffering and anger held by billions of beings on the planet right now. we're making more space within ourselves to access our sovereign identity  and are elevated consciousness.
•
take the time you need to be gentle and recover, to self-care, to find appreciation and joy in the process.
•
(rest in the comments 👇🏼)

in order to get to the beach you have to climb down the face of a cliff, through some debris and the whole time you’re sort of slipping because the sand makes for a slippery slope. ˙pǝsınɹq 'ǝɹos :ʞɔǝu ʎɯ ˙uǝןןoʍs 'pǝsınɹq 'ƃuıqqoɹɥʇ :ǝןdɯǝʇ ʇɟǝן puɐ ʇɥƃıɹ ʎɯ ˙ʇno pǝssɐd :ǝɯ ˙pɐǝɥ ǝɥʇ uı ǝɯ ƃuıɥɔund :ɯıɥ ˙ǝuƃoןoɔ sɐ ןoɥoɔןɐ :ɯıɥ ˙ƃuıuǝddɐɥ s’ʇɐɥʍ ƃuıuoıʇsǝnb :ʎƃƃoɹƃ 'ǝɯ ˙uǝdo ʇı ƃuıʞɔıʞ :ǝuoǝɯos ˙pǝʞɔoן ɹoop ǝɥʇ ɥʇıʍ pǝq ǝןƃuıs ɐ uı ƃuıdǝǝןs :ǝɯ ˙sʇɹoɥs puɐ ǝıpooɥ ɐ uı dǝǝןsɐ ƃuıןןɐɟ :ǝɯ
when your feet hit the bottom, there’s a swing chained to the pier; half on the beach, half in the ocean (depending on the tide). :::ǝǝs ʇ’uop noʎ ʇɐɥʇ ןןɐ sı sıɥʇ ؛puɐɥ ƃuıpuǝʇxǝ ɹnoʎ ʎq ɯɐ ı pǝıɟıɹɹoɥ ʎןǝʇnןosqɐ ʍoɥ ǝǝs noʎ uǝɥʍ '”ʞɔnɟ ǝɥʇ ʇɐɥʍ“ ǝʞıן ǝɯ ʇɐ ʞooן noʎ uǝɥʍ os ˙pǝןʇıʇuǝ ɹo pǝʍoןןɐ ʇou ǝɹ’noʎ ˙ǝɯ ɥɔnoʇ ʇou uɐɔ noʎ ˙ǝʇɐןnɔıʇɹɐ uɐɔ ı uɐɥʇ ǝɹoɯ sıɥʇ oʇ ʞɔɐq oƃ ı 
something has always been soothing about the sound of water, like rain or the current of a river, but especially the ocean.

text: i am so humbled to say i shared my poem “broken” with an amazing community saturday. this is dedicated to the man who sexually harassed and assaulted me for over 6 months until i had to leave my job the week of christmas. the guy who told me to not wiggle. the guy who left bruises on my neck. the guy who spit in my mouth in the meijer parking lot and called me a slut. the guy who tried setting me up over two zips. the dude who didn’t like me telling him no and spreading rumors to my family. and finally, to the broken soul who left me for dead two weeks ago. you may be broken, but because of you...i’m exponentially stronger than you’ll ever be. #alleycatcafe #poetry #slam #abuse #ptsd #copingskills #healwithwords #inspired #supported #empath #speakout #tellyourstory #metoo #abusesurvivor #empath #hsp #doneprotectingthedemons

text:
excerpt from the infamy confession ● 
kalima riley stood next to the large window, as the early morning sun, shined through the capacious room; creating the most beautiful rainbow on her white, silk blouse. the multitude of fascinating colors, immediately reminded her of the last time she seen her father: franklin miro. she was twelve years old, living on the island of kauai, hawaii. ●

the thoughts of her father, quickly invaded her emotions, without warning or permission. immediately, she remembered the bumpy, short drive to the wailua falls lookout. her father spoke so passionately about forgiveness and the importance of gaining an education: “kalima...precious daughter of mine. you have to understand...education should be the most important part of your life. it should be more important than breathing, more important than sleeping. regardless of the situation, you should never let anyone...even jesus christ himself...hinder your ability to gain an education. if bullies are the problem, then you fight the bullies! win or lose, you will be respected amongst your peers. look at me kalima!! anyone, who threatens your ability to gain knowledge, should be approached with violence! and there’s something else you should always remember...education is more than just textbooks. a real education...is about the lessons we learn in life.” ●

kalima began to think more deeply, about what her father said on the bridge. but at that time in her life, she hated school. it wasn’t the teachers, or the educational curriculum she hated ― it was the students, the bullies. the black girls envied her natural beauty and her long, natural black hair. the white boys made jokes about the size of her butt and her full lips. and most of the black boys, tried to convince her to give them oral sex. school was awful and definitely more stressful than she ever imagined. she wanted to runway and quit ― but her father’s “educational theory” ― gave her a new perspective.

kalima began to think more deeply, about what her father said on the bridge. but at that time in her life, she hated school. it wasn’t the teachers, or the educational curriculum she hated ― it was the students, the bullies. the black girls envied her natural beauty and her long, natural black hair. the white boys made jokes about the size of her butt and her full lips. and most of the black boys, tried to convince her to give them oral sex. school was awful and definitely more stressful than she ever imagined. she wanted to runway and quit ― but her father’s “educational theory” ― gave her a new perspective.

text:
feeling angry? or can’t understand why so many women around you are full of rage? either way, visit brooklyn’s greenlight bookstore this thursday 7:30pm to hear me interview soraya chemaly, author of “rage becomes her: the power of women’s anger.” we’ll discuss how your emotion intersects with political action and social change, and make specific suggestions about healthy, productive outlets for difficult feelings — as opposed to the many unhealthy, unproductive techniques many of us often practice. 😂 
the event is free; all are welcome.

text:
[story series, 8 of 9] 💟 we are now past the  #kavanaugh hearing where #christineblaseyford bravely testified regarding her experience of sexual assault. .
.
. 💟numerous women are reliving their own past traumas, including experiencing recall of traumas they had not thought of in years or even decades. .
.
💟i know there are men who support dr. ford and are vehemently against rape culture and sexual violence against women. i see it in some of the men i know, on television, and through social media. .
.
💟however, what i am rarely seeing in the men i know is an interest in how i am doing in the midst of the #metoo and #timesup movements and my work with #traumaqueen. .
.
💟now, one could argue that perhaps these men in my life don’t know what to say and fear making me upset at the mere mention of the topic of trauma and sexual assault. maybe they have no idea what i’ve been doing with trauma queen (unlikely, but maybe). maybe they are providing support to other women in their lives and calling out other mens’ unacceptable behavior in ways i am unable to see. .
.
💟i’ve had heated conversations with a handful of men in my life recently who, instead of being curious about my feelings, experiences, and viewpoints — are immediately defensive, offended, and angry. .
.
💟that in itself is the problem. if i express that i feel alone and in need of support and conversations from the men in my life, how does it make any sense to tear me down as a response to that? this expression is a call to action, and not the kind that makes me or any other survivor the one to blame. .
.
. 💟if you are a man reading this, are you offended by what i’m saying? if so, why? if you are leaning in to discussions with women, asking us how we are doing, and serving as a leader for other men — what is there to be offended about? .
.
💟i do not expect for every single male acquaintance or colleague to run to every woman they know and tug on their sleeve, asking to know how we are and recount experiences of sexual assault. .
.
💟i am asking for a pause. when women express their grief, loneliness, and anger about sexual violence — please, take a pause and find your empathy. 🕉🙏

text:
sending love to anyone else out there who has felt the weight of these past few weeks on their heart like i have— and a gentle reminder to spend some time doing whatever makes you feel whole, loved, and safe 
for me that means spending more time with my #1 (me!) in meditation, enjoying the company of loved ones, and generally being kinder to myself

we could all use a little more self-love in our lives and i hope you make time for yourself today, you’re worth it 😘

#selfcare #selfcarefirst #selflove #meditation #wellness #whole #happy #love #loved #ibelieveher #metoo

text:
october is national domestic violence awareness month. 💜
domestic violence affects millions, both women and men, of every race, religion, culture and status. it’s not just punches and black eyes -- it’s yelling, humiliation, stalking, manipulation, coercion, threats and isolation. it can be physical, mental, emotional, any or all of the above. 
your story can be the #1thing that is a catalyst to help, inspire, or motivate others to help end domestic violence.
#dvam2018 is aimed to help spread awareness of the unfortunate growing issue of domestic violence and getting involved in the effort to end domestic violence. 
follow the #1thing hashtag all month long for stories of survivors, advocates, and get informed! 
i’ll be posting my own stories, as well as resources and statistics throughout the month! i have nothing but love and support to give & so much that i need to share! stay tuned!

text: it's a story that's gripped america, shaken survivors of sexual assault, and galvanised women around the world. there's a lot of chaos in trump's america that it's easy to tune out, but this moment is worth explaining. last week, dr christine blasey ford testified in a senate hearing about a chilling sexual assault she experienced in high school. one of the perpetrators, she says, was brett kavanaugh - a us judge who has been nominated for one of the most powerful and important jobs in america - as a justice of the supreme court. 20 million people in america watched dr blasey ford testify last friday, and her account has sparked a massive response in the #metoo movement. want to wrap your head around the case and understand more? 🤔 we've explained the story on our podcast. stream or download yesterday's episode on any podcasting app on your phone, or hit the link in our bio to listen back on our website.

text:
this is me. i am a domestic violence survivor. for a very long time i was a victim, but now i choose to be more. now i choose to take my voice back and use it for good. it has taken me almost an entire decade to say these words out loud.
.
i still have pain. i still cry. i still struggle with the aftermath. i still wonder what i should have done differently. i still worry what others will think of me. i still have moments where i am ashamed....but these moments are short lived. .
i share my story now to encourage victims to speak up, ask for help, and never stop fighting for freedom. you are not alone. it is not your fault. this is not love. .
october is domestic violence awareness month. join me in support of all the survivors, the victims still fighting, and the angels who never found their way out by wearing purple. such a simple gesture could be the beacon of light that someone is desperately searching for. 💜
.
.
#wearedvpi #domesticviolencesurvivor #awareness #endthesilence #stoptheviolence #youarenotalone #loveshouldnthurt #metoo #takeyourvoiceback #bestrong #speakup #october #wearpurple #purplehair #iamproudofmyself #youareloved #nevergiveup #likeaphoenix #iwillrise

text:
i was 16, i was drunk, i was never taught what rape was. i was 17, i thought it was normal to be pressured into it. i was 18, i was naive and in denial. i was 20 after giving up on sex for a year and a half, learning not so soon after that it should of stayed that way. they were my boyfriend, my best friend, my coworker. not listening when i say no, not caring when i push away or try to leave. it happens so much that nobody cares enough to do anything about it, or even educate anyone about it. i’m 20, i just learned that’s there’s more than one kind of rape. i’m your friend, i’m your sister, i’m your niece, i’m your daughter, i’m you. a beautiful little girl with a bright future, honour roll all throughout school, too many talents to count. now, i’m a statistic. 1 out of 3 women have been sexual abused in some way, shape or form in their lives. out of all the stories i’ve heard, people i’ve talked to, i think there’s a lot more than just every 1 in 3. i’m 20. i just learned there’s more than one kind of rape. 
if anyone, boys included, ever need someone to talk to that won’t judge them, message me. if you are in a situation you can’t find a way out of, let me help. just because we are apart of the statistic, doesn’t mean we have to live like we are. i love my life no matter how many times the rollercoaster goes down, because it always goes back up and i will not let them ruin the entire ride, and you shouldn’t either. 
i’ve been seeing all of the posts this past month, and i think it’s our time. free yourself, tell your story, even if it’s to a friend or an anonymous website, or a piece of paper you’re going to burn. don’t let them control you, they don’t own you. 
#rapevictim #rapeculture #rapesurvivor #statistics #survivor #friend #metoo #metoomovement

text:
não achamos que é bem assim, sr. nando reis!

não! nando reis não está errado quando diz que é preciso olhar mais para o que está ao nosso redor, e que o “amor pode estar do seu lado” e tudo mais!

mas recebemos em nossos consultórios inúmeras pessoas com uma história de vida onde a falta de um olhar generoso para si trouxe tantas angustias que acreditamos que sim, é preciso olhar mais pra dentro e que isso não é desperdício nenhum.

acreditamos que existe uma linha muito tênue entre olhar para si e não ser egoísta, e olhar para o outro e se anular.

acreditamos também que não há uma fórmula mágica! que cada um deve encontrar o limite que lhe cabe, que lhe é saudável!
já pensou nisso? qual o seu limite? ***********
nós, do @mariasinteiras realizamos atendimento presencial e on-line de acordo com as especificações do cfp.

text:
"we don’t even bother to talk about the woman after her failed attempt to pursue justice. she’s been living with trauma for possibly years, finally decided to put it all on the line and relive her trauma for just a shot at justice, she loses, and everyone moves on. she still has to bear the burden of that trauma with no justice–– and even worse, she now has to do it while the public doesn’t even believe her.
.
that’s what reporting a sexual assault is like nearly every time, regardless of how public it becomes: when the survivor loses her case or the report amounts to nothing, everyone else moves on while she has to live with her trauma not being believed for the rest of her life."
-
read the rest of my piece "to not be believed: why i support the dr. christine blasey fords of the world" - link in the bio.
.
.
.

text:
i am not triggered. that word is too small. i am furious. i am screaming. i am overwhelmed, underwhelmed, heart broken and seething. i am exhausted from being silenced. i am weeping for everyone who does feel triggered or frightened right now. i am weary of quantifying my trauma and feeling 'lucky'. i am enraged at a world that makes these things seem small in comparison. i want to throat punch every 'good guy' who just doesn't get it - who refuses to acknowledge their own varying degrees of bullshit and thinks not being the devil makes them a fucking saint. i want to shake every woman who is so brainwashed she hurls rocks at her sisters so she can stand on their backs.
.
i want to offer safe space and a huge apology to so many - because i understand that being white presenting, cis, and in a heteronormative relationship means i have a ton of unearned privilege.
.
.
i want to thank everyone who stands up and offer strength to everyone who isn't there yet. you are loved.
.
i want to tell allies that being a silent ally is not enough anymore. you need to be an enemy to our enemies. you need to fight. not for your daughters, sisters, or mothers but for who they are regardless of their relation to anyone other than themselves.

triggered? no. we passed triggered in january. .
i see you. i am you. i believe you. .
.
.
#believesurvivors #believewomen #endrapeculture #ibelieveher #ibelievechristineblaseyford #consentmatters #coercionisnotconsent #metoo

#repost @surviving_a_narc

don’t ever silence yourself because talking about it helps yourself to process. processing is essential in healing. not talking about it can cause brain-altering changes because you haven’t had a chance to process the how’s, why’s and what ifs. it could cause a higher risk of allowing this behavior to repeat itself, because you continue to silence the abuse and forgive the abuser. they call it “speaking out” for a reason. i find that the more i talk about my abuse, the more people i help, the more aware i’ve become about my situation and the more silenced my abuser becomes since he’s aware that i’m not longer afraid to out him. speaking about it will not cause further trauma, but the polar opposite. keeping this inside will tear one apart, can cause depression, anxiety and even suicidal thoughts which—surprise—can lead to suicide. don’t ever feel ashamed and don’t ever silence yourself!!

text:
i want to hate you. and sometimes...at my worst times...i do. 
and then i have to look at you again in my head. look you in the eyes and say "i forgive you. i don't hate you. i don't blame you." i want to hate you. and sometimes...at my loneliest...when i feel like i'm the only person in the world, with screaming kids,  dishes piled high, my floors covered in crumbs...i do. 
because i can't breathe. i can't move. 
but then i have to look at you again in my head. look at every moment i was trapped and couldn't move and say
"i forgive you. i don't hate you. i don't blame you." i want to hate you and sometimes when i can't look at my husband because of shame...i do. 
but then, even when i feel your chains trying to hold me down, i get up. i get up and fight. 
i get up, crying, and tell you i love you. because you made me, me. 
you took my voice, but then because of your actions, gave me a different voice. 
one to fight for my daughter and sons. 
one to fight for my marriage. 
one to fight for others. 
you do not get the last word. 
ever. 
#proverbs31woman #womenoffaith #wellwateredwomen #graceupongrace #shereadstruth #godstruth #soulscripts #gritandgrace #gritandvirtue #christianblogger #faith #healing #sexuabuse #sexualabuseawareness #metoo

⠀
son 28 las que firmaron una declaración en la que ponen de manifiesto acosos y abusos sufridos durante sus años de cursada en el prestigioso colegio preuniversitario. un alegato que leyeron frente a un aula magna colmada durante el acto de egreso, junto a familiares, docentes y preceptores. ⠀
⠀
durante 10 minutos, con sus pañuelos verdes toman la palabra contando los abusos de poder recibidos, los chistes misóginos que les hicieron, los comentarios diarios alrededor de la ropa con la que se vestían para cursar y también los casos de acoso sexual por parte de docentes, preceptores y autoridades que vivieron durante los cinco años de cursada.⠀
“regente, vicerrectores, rector: ya no le tenemos miedo a sus sanciones”, los increpan,. “¿qué piensan de todo esto cuando se jactan de la supuesta excelencia académica que corre por estos claustros? ¿la violencia institucional también es uno de los pilares sobre los que se asienta el prestigio que reviste a este aula magna?”.⠀
"no habernos escuchado fue una decisión política que hoy ya no pueden tomar. les arrebatamos este espacio para brindarles esas respuestas que van a marcar el camino a seguir a partir de ahora", agregaron. ⠀

text:
i’ve been constantly feeling uneasy and sick to my stomach. lately, i’ve been feeling very sensitive and very volatile. i’ve always felt unsafe. i’ve always felt afraid. i’ve always felt alone. (begin rant) i am a victim of sexual assault and i will not tolerate the nonsense of “boys will be boys”. i will not tolerate the question, “what were you wearing when it happened?” i will not tolerate, “why did he/she wait so long to come forward?” because of these questions, i freeze up and have panic attacks quite regularly. some of my closest friends and even my family — i repeat, even my family, don’t know my trauma. some of these people (without knowing, of course) are direct triggers for my anxiety attacks and those questions are the usually the culprit. why people still think that those questions are appropriate? i don’t know. call me crazy, but i believe none of those questions matter. plain and simple, i believe rapists cause rape. so be sensitive to those around you. understand that those questions are offensive and they contribute to the rape culture that keep women like me from feeling safe. (rant over)

despite all this, today has been good to me. i still feel unsafe, i’m still very afraid, but i don’t feel alone anymore.

#metoomovement #metoo #ibelieveher

text: in high school, a group of girls spread rumors my first month of school. because of those rumors, boys used to touch me inappropriately. a boy came in the bathroom once. another boy i was sitting next to during a rainy day of p.e. and he put his hand up my skirt, i cried while he touched me. i tried to tell a friend and a family member, they wouldn't listen. my junior year of high school, i dated a boy who liked to push me around. i never told anyone because i was afraid of him. one night, he pulled the car down a side street by my house and he raped me. i have only told 2 people in my entire life because i never wanted anyone to tell me i was lying. a friend took me to the police to report it, the police asked if i was just lying to protect my reputation. i was humiliated and destroyed so i told them sorry for wasting their time. in college, a man assaulted me while i was working at my school in the evening. i reported it to the school and the police. the police told me that they couldn't find him then asked if i was lying because i had cheated on my boyfriend. i have kept a lot of this to myself. many of you, including my family closest to me, have never known any of this. i'm sorry i kept it a secret. but when so many people tell you that it's not true, you feel so broken. you feel so hurt. i keep quiet and feel sick when i see these women come forward and have everyone call them liars and whores. it's heartbreaking and keeps other women quiet. but i cannot be quiet anymore. this is my story and it hurts to tell it but i encourage everyone to tell theirs. do not let anyone silence you. i believe you. #metoo #survivor #whyinevertold #stopkavanaugh

text:
i have such gratitude for the bravery of christine blasey ford. it is no easy task for a survivor to come out and talk about their sexual trauma, let alone talk about it in front of the entire world. christine is a true hero! christine is another strong face of the #metoo movement. 
watching christine's strength this past week, has me reflecting on the bravery and strength of all the women who attend my #metoo support groups! they all have stepped out of the shadows and into the light...to break open their trauma and start the healing journey. 
healing from our trauma can be empowering and supportive when we have a community of other women to heal together with. i am hopeful that we are heading in the right direction. together, we can do this!!! together, we are strong!!! #metoo #believesurvivors #womenunite #supporteachother

military-hester-the more i think about this, the more excited i get! will i look the way i pictured myself when i walk on stage? no. 👋🏽 will i look like the other women who compete next to me? probably not. 🤷🏼‍♀️ am i going to be extremely proud? hell to the yes! 👏🏽👏🏽👏🏽 i am not doing this to place. 🙅🏼‍♀️ this journey was very personal. 💕 this journey wasn’t just for me. 🙏🏽 i am proud because i did not give up. 🙌🏽 i am proud because even though i’ve fallen of track a few times, i did not call it quits. 🙌🏽 i am proud because i’ve learned so much about my body throughout this entire experience! 🙌🏽 most importantly, i am proud because i showed my child that no matter what age you become, no matter what life throws your way, you can and most certainly will make your dreams come true with a little hard work, dedication and a sprinkle of magic of course! ✨

text:
it was good to see senator flake have a change of heart and ask for an fbi investigation before the vote for a new supreme court justice. maybe he was thinking of his daughters and granddaughters. this portrait was taken for politico magazine where we asked senators to bring something that most defined why they had run for office. it was also good to see his honesty in last nights @60minutes interview but also heart breaking.  he basically said there is no reason to make decisions in the interests of the country, just to choose party lines if you want to get reelected.  sad days indeed.  here’s the transcript from that exchange.  pelley: senator flake, you've announced that you're not running for re-election and i wonder, could you have done this, if you were running for re-election?
flake: no, not a chance.
pelley: not a chance?
flake: no, no.
pelley: because politics has become too sharp, too partisan?
flake: there's no value to reaching across the aisle. there's no currency for that anymore. there's no incentive.

text:
pt.2 what did fdr mean when he said "presidents are selected, not elected"? “… selected, not elected.” whoa…
towards the end, in november, the populace gets to vote for someone to fill the office of president. there was, however, a lot more to the process before and after. and remember, we are talking about the 1930s and 1940s, not the current times. back in those days, the country had a.m. radio, and lots of newspapers, as “mass media” to communicate with the people…
first of all, the political parties were more or less run by political “machines”. in the absence of other methods of mass media, most people depended on the political machines and their “slate” of candidates and issues.
these machines — both democratic and republican — proffered candidates and issues that would push their agenda. once the machines had made their selections, the final choices of each party would be settled in a convention
talk about smoke-filled rooms… there were lots of them in those days.
the people would finally get to vote in the “presidential election”, but even that “election” did not finalize things. once the people had voted, “electors” in each state would vote for the candidates, more or less according to how each of their states had voted. it has been this vote by the electors (each state gets one elector for each us senator and us rep. — i.e., md. gets 8+2, vt. gets 1+2, etc.) that was actually the presidential election.
our presidential election, with electors and all, is a unique process. it is not really one election, but 54 simultaneous elections, and ensures that candidates will make at least a token show in every state or territory.

our presidential election, with electors and all, is a unique process. it is not really one election, but 54 simultaneous elections, and ensures that candidates will make at least a token show in every state or territory.

text: i feel this. god, i feel this so much. every second of every day is a trigger, and i want to put my head under the covers. but i’m fighting that instinct because i hid for long enough, and i have no reason to feel ashamed. i’m not sorry if your sick of hearing me scream “rape survivor,” i don’t give a fuck because of that second word - i survived. and every time i tell my story, another woman comes to me privately with her own, and i am so unbelievably honored to shoulder a piece of their pain by speaking out & listening. so i’m not hiding, i’m crusading. i’m leaning on my loved ones rather than hiding. if you can’t say aloud what happened to you, just know the two most important words a rape survivor can hear: i believe you. #rapesurvivor #metoo #isupportsurvivors #isupportwomen #fuckthepatriarchy #ibelieveher

towards the end, in november, the populace gets to vote for someone to fill the office of president. there was, however, a lot more to the process before and after. and remember, we are talking about the 1930s and 1940s, not the current times. back in those days, the country had a.m. radio, and lots of newspapers, as “mass media” to communicate with the people…
first of all, the political paies were more or less run by political “machines”. in the absence of other methods of mass media, most people depended on the political machines and their “slate” of candidates and issues.
these machines — both democratic and republican — proffered candidates and issues that would push their agenda. once the machines had made their selections, the final choices of each pay would be settled in a convention
talk about smoke-filled rooms… there were lots of them in those days.
the people would finally get to vote in the “presidential election”, but even that “election” did not finalize things. once the people had voted, “electors” in each state would vote for the candidates, more or less according to how each of their states had voted. it has been this vote by the electors (each state gets one elector for each us senator and us rep. — i.e., md. gets 8+2, vt. gets 1+2, etc.) that was actually the presidential election.
our presidential election, with electors and all, is a unique process. it is not really one election, but 54 simultaneous elections, and ensures that candidates will make at least a token show in every state or territory.

text:
#whyididntreport the first time it happened, i was too young to understand that what happened to me was considered sexual assault. and the second time it happened, when i told the person that was supposed to defend me, nothing happened. follow that with years of fear, shame, anxiety, and depression. 
but, the stain on my childhood that i looked at with the biggest grief and shame i no longer look at that way. because i know it is redeemed through god. and also, because i know that the statistics of 1 of 5 women and 1 of 4 children that i fall into will one sweet joyous day will be no longer. our voices still matter, even though we didn’t report it. because we survived it. #metoo #sexualassaultsurvivor #ourvoicesmatter #nolongerlivingwithshame

text:
i didn’t tell anyone for five years when i was 18. surprisingly, many wait much longer to tell, if they tell at all. .
.
sexual abuse is invasive and slithery. it moves in ways that leaves the victim shattered and feeling as if their very mind and soul has been altered. somehow, we default to shame.  ie: “this was my fault. i wanted this to happen.”
.
.
i’ve spent decades overcoming the decisions i’ve made to harm myself for this very abuse. but, in the end: i addressed it. it was hard as hell. it was a very lonely road. but, the damage done was severe.  and, i walk a lot more freely than i did before...by going back to the pain. .
.
today, someone is taking a hit as her motives and trauma come under question. no matter where you stand, do know, anyone who has experienced sexual abuse views life through a different lens. there is always an extra layer of grief when grieving. always an extra layer of pain when hurting. not only do i believe her, but i’m overwhelmed by her ability to share it under such weighty circumstances. .
.
no matter the outcome, i hope she is held tonight.  i hope she is surrounded by the people who see her as her whole self and i hope they scoop her in to their arms and remind her that she is safe.... but, just a whole lot more known because now here is an army of quiet soldiers who have a leader broadening a path for them to heal. thank you, dr. ford.  #ibelieveher

text:
“3 years ago, i was boarding a train in india to see the taj mahal. happy, free, working and living my dream job as a photojournalist. but what only 4 people have known since then, is that one week prior i was again sexually assaulted. besides contacting my therapist immediately after, i told no one for the nearly two-month duration that i was in india. perhaps because i didn’t want to go through the re-traumatization of my first assault, which included a grueling two-year trial process. whatever the reason, i chose not to report or tell anyone. and...that’s ok.

as a national survivor speaker and advocate, i’ve dedicated the past seven years of my life to sharing my painful truth with the world—with the mission of bringing other survivors hope and comfort. although i have been outspoken about being brutally raped by a stranger who helped me change my tire in 2009, this was a part of my past that i chose to keep private.

with the newest #whyididntreport movement, which aims to shed light on this issue and the silencing of survivors, i’m reminded of the hundreds of survivors i’ve met and spoken to since the start of the #metoo movement. the survivors who (after hearing my story and countless other stories in their news-feeds and mainstream media) felt “ashamed,” “guilty” or “like less of a survivor” for not going public with their stories or reporting it. and for the survivors who did go forward, many told me that they experienced re-traumatization because they weren’t ready for that step—causing serious setbacks in their recovery.

the #metoo and #whyididntreport movements are crucial and so necessary. but in talking with survivors, i’m finding that these movements can also be damaging to those who choose to process in private.

i share my story now to remind survivors that there's no one way to handle the aftermath of an assault. that it's ok to share on social media, & it's also ok to process it quietly on their own. simply put, survivors owe their story to no one, not even the police. we must find ways to be more inclusive of all survivors' choices, stories, circumstances & recoveries.” - brittany p. #pouryourheartout

text:
i’ve been struggling with how to and if i should contribute to the voices of incredibly strong, informed, influential women at this time.
•
as i was contemplating what to write in this post today, i was waiting on castmates at the grocery store.
•
i stared off into space and a man walked by me, leaned in close to my face, and told me to “smile! it ain’t that bad!”
•
minutes later, two men checking out in line stared at me to the point of discomfort. i thought i could make them stop by looking directly at them as they passed me. instead, my gaze was met with them leering and sniggering at the fact that they had gotten my attention.
•
these instances are nothing compared to the harassment that other women have gone through. but they are a testament to what a woman experiences in mere moments while doing something as simple as standing at a grocery store.
•
women leave the house having to worry about their safety, personal space, and body language just so that they can live life without harassment.
•
women, i see you. i hear you when you say you wish you could join an all-women’s gym or wear a cloak so that you avoid trouble from just having a female body.
•
allies of women, i thank you. i am grateful that not all men are like this and long for a day when this movement results in women feeling as safe to be themselves as men are.
•
i’m so sickened and saddened that sometimes i don’t feel like my voice or energy matters. but we’ve got to keep fighting. women deserve to be heard, believed, and made safe. i love you and i’m here for you.

text:
tuesday love note courtesy of @sharonsalzberg 
today i am going to be kind to myself and my body, and resist the urge to ‘do’ that is triggered in the absence of positive reinforcement. how will you be kind today? 
i’m often asked how to get volunteer or paid work overseas or in the social sectors and my first line of enquiry is always around intention. why? what is the change you want to see around you? how does it relate to the change you seek in your feeling state? 
to make the most impact in support of a better world, it is necessary to also start close in. to first, reduce the harm we inflict on ourselves and others through judgement, separation and untruths: to become conscious of our own triggers and hurts and how we might be projecting them onto others. to understand how our drive to help others may also be a pattern of behaviour that has been born from fear. to learn how to harness our enormous desire for transformation and change without burning out or becoming afraid of not succeeding. 
changing the world starts close in ..: with kindness and awareness and compassion for ourselves and others. we don’t always get to see the outcome of this kindness, but it is the simplest and most pure form of social change we can affect... and so we trust that our kindness is alchemising and a salve for ourselves and others in this harsh world: from this place our work is more empowered, more equal, more aligned with our soul gifts and in support of our common humanity. 
when we meet our desire to do better with awareness and insight; we are transformed into warrior goddesses ready to do the work regardless of the ego’s desire to be recognised. 
#socialchange #sacredcircle #femininerising #socialjustice #metoo #womenempowerment #womenscoach #personaldevelopmentcoach #mindfulnesscoach #yogaoffthemat #bethechangeyouwanttosee #womenchangingtheworld #womenchagemakers #spiritualfeminism #sacredactivism

text:
after 40 years on this earth, i’m still wondering what it would be like to move through life without regard to my appearance. i was raised to believe that my looks are very important for things like being liked, being paid attention to, being worthy, being accepted.
simple stuff like getting ready to go to a rehearsal, which is my job, reminds me that i subconsciously think being attractive is part of my job. and it’s not. my job is to sing the sh*t out of everything with as much heart as i can offer.
-
-

thanks for being here with me today, grandma. i know you went through so much violence too, and i carry that trauma in my blood. and you are also one of the most powerful women i will ever know.  i’m both comforted and enraged that we share these experiences, but thank you for reminding me that i’m not alone. i’m committed to healing for you and all my ancestors, and for all those yet to come. i love and miss you so much. .
.

text: dear love, go out into the world each day without fear. when you return to me, bring me your pain, your shame, and hurt, and worry. take it off and hand it to me. never be afraid that it is ruined, or that i might get upset. i am unfazed. there isn't a stain i haven't made myself, or seen, or heard about. we will wash it out together. we'll treat it. we'll wash it twice if we have to. we'll hang it to dry in the sun. if it rains, that's ok too, because even the sky has to let it out. the sun will return. and when you go out again the next day, you can wear your skin again with pride. we will have scrubbed it and dried it and ironed it out together. it won't be worn out or show signs of wear. we will have cleaned it delicately. and you'll be able to help other girls and boys with their hurt and sadness and pain. you'll be able to help them wash their fears away. you'll tell them that it's ok when their hands get dirty or their shirt gets wet with tears. you'll know how to wring it all out and dry it. i'll teach you how to use your love to wash it all away. because when you are made of love, you cannot be ruined. you may need to dust yourself off, but you cannot be broken, my angel. each day is a chance to remember what you are made of. each thread of you was woven specifically to make perfection. carry that with you. remind others of how beautiful their colors are. tell them that they will never fade, that vintage is special, that every pattern is unique, and that a tear can be mended. bring it to me. we'll clean it together. i promise to send you out tomorrow as good as new. #girlpower #loveisallyouneed #youmatter #weareone #standup #whorunstheworld #littlemama #metoo #nofear #youcansitwithus #ihaveyourback #womenempowerment #girlsrule #girlsaregreat #bekind

text:
what are we to do about the suffering which is all around us? we help where we can but also need to take care of ourselves and not let our heart become tarnished with despair. yes, there are buddhist practices such as tonglen which work at transforming suffering but this type of activity is also held in the nembutsu. when we recite ‘amida buddha’ we bring amida’s attention here into this world, upon ourselves and those around us. so reciting while keeping someone suffering in mind opens up assistance of the deep karmic kind. if it is appropriate and possible to encourage them to recite themselves there is far greater benefit in that they, also, assure their birth in the pure land.

is it magic? no. it is simply a buddha actively seeking to help beings directed to ourselves or others. yes, we can feel helpless and overwhelmed by so much suffering in this world. rather than become doubtful or discouraged it should encourage us to recite more frequently with deepening faith. our motivation is to escape the unskillfulness we possess in this life which prevents us from helping others on the deepest levels of the spirit. once in the pure land our enlightenment is assured at which time we gain incredible capacity to save others from lifetime after lifetime of frustrated desires and contact with all which is unpleasant. #amida #buddha #suffering #dukha #amitabha #enlightenment #survivor #metoo #hopeless #nembutsu #amituofo #samsara

text:
meet porsha daniels, @honey_kush_smiley 
on february 3, 2015
porsha daniels from houston texas became a victim of domestic violence. she’s suffered a broken collar bone, punctured liver and also lost a kidney. in addition, porsha also suffered 22 stab wounds to her neck, hands and stomach. help us as we stand in solidarity and support of porsha daniels, a then, wheelchair bound young woman who’s strength and determination has now allowed her to stand tall today! 
porsha daniels, on this first day of domestic violence awareness month, we honor, support and uplift you! your brave and courageous spirit and will to survive is a testament to how good god is! your story brings awareness and offers hope and light to us all and we thank you so much for sharing!

text:
"regrets collect like old friends
here to relive your darkest moments.
i can see no way, i can see no way.
and all of the ghouls come out to play.

and every demon wants his pound of flesh
but i like to keep some things to myself.
i like to keep my issues drawn.
it's always darkest before the dawn.

and i've been a fool and i've been blind.
i can never leave the past behind.
i can see no way, i can see no way.
i'm always dragging that horse around.

all of his questions, such a mournful sound.
tonight i'm gonna bury that horse in the ground.
so i like to keep my issues drawn.
but it's always darkest before the dawn

shake it out, shake it out, shake it out, shake it out.
shake it out, shake it out, shake it out, shake it out. and it's hard to dance with a devil on your back
so shake him off!

and i am done with my graceless heart
so tonight i'm gonna cut it out and then restart
'cause i like to keep my issues drawn
it's always darkest before the dawn

shake it out, shake it out, shake it out, shake it out.
shake it out, shake it out, shake it out, shake it out.
and it's hard to dance with a devil on your back
so shake him off

and it's hard to dance with a devil on your back
and given half the chance would i take any of it back.
it's a fine romance but it's left me so undone. 
it's always darkest before the dawn.

and i'm damned if i do and i'm damned if i don't.
so here's to drinks in the dark at the end of my road.
and i'm ready to suffer and i'm ready to hope.
it's a shot in the dark aimed right at my throat
'cause looking for heaven, found the devil in me.
looking for heaven, found the devil in me.
well what the hell i'm gonna let it happen to me, yeah

shake it out, shake it out, shake it out, shake it out.
shake it out, shake it out, shake it out, shake it out.
and it's hard to dance with a devil on your back
so shake him off." ~ @florence @florenceandthemachine

text:
let's be very very clear here: in order to cause any amount of harm to another person requires you to de-humanize them to some degree. 
in my mind, any degree of de-humanizing is an act of violence. 
so when we witness or perpetrate any act of harm we are choosing to see another as less than human and are the cause of violence. 
we are all active participants in this and it buys right into separation rather than oneness. often it stems from unconscious biases, which we have a resonant responsibility to root out and heal to the highest degree possible in this lifetime. 
we are by nature programmed for this. the primal (or amygdala) portion of the brain will do everything in its power to keep us safe. this means that any perceived threat will cause a fight or flight reaction; hence the de-humanizing leading to violence. do not use this as an excuse. 
society has also programmed us for de-humanizing, through patriarchy dating back centuries and the attempt by colonizers to eradicate poc, particularly black and indigenous in north america and around the world once we could no longer legally enslave them. 
we are thinking, feeling and evolving beings with the capacity to change old programming and behaviors. it is, in fact, paramount to our survival as a species. 
so today go inward and begin the long and worthy journey of facing all your violence. it is there, i promise you. you are violent to yourself all the fucking time in big and small ways and it leaks out from there. do this work with urgency and deep compassion. move through the inevitable guilt and shame as quickly as possible. its usefulness is extremely limited. 
it's time because #timesup #metoo #blacklivesmatter #indigenousrights #spiritualbadass #raiseyourvibration #loveismyreligion 
love,
jill

text_retweet:
#repost @danii_fit
• • • • •
it’s time to have a talk. i have always been transparent with you all on here and on twitter so if you don’t follow me on twitter, i’m about to say what i said last night. •••••
i don’t want sympathy i just want my story to be heard. i want to explain #whyididntreport and to let people know that they are not alone. •••••
it’s been 17 years since the last time i was sexually abused. yes the last time. it happened not once, not twice but, multiple times. i was 6 when it started. it happened wherever my uncle could get me alone. family party with too many people? let’s skip it today. babysitting me? perfect alone time! and it kept happening because i was too young to know that what was happening was wrong. and then after that when i did realize what was going on, i became strong and told him to fuck off. i felt shameful and held it in for years to come. 7 years to be exact. when i finally came out with it... no one believed me except my parents, brother, and grandma. i’ll have you know i have a large family. for that many people to not believe me broke me. how do you not believe someone??? how?? what did i have to lose except my entire family??? •••••
the worst was when we were on a family vacation to bethany beach and my family was upstairs playing cards and i had to use the bathroom but someone was upstairs. i went downstairs really fast and he trapped me in a bedroom on the lower floor. locked me in. i screamed. •••••
no one heard me. i cried. my dad asked why i was upset when i went back upstairs. i told him i fell. he asked to see my legs to check for bruising (i have anemia so ice is my best friend). no bruises. he didn’t question it. next day i wanted to go back to the house from the beach but it was a far walk so my parents didn’t want to bring me back so my uncle offered. i said no it’s okay i’m fine here and they were like you made a big fuss now go. what was i supposed to do? i went and when i was showering he entered the bathroom and well, i don’t even have to say what happened next because it’s not pretty. •••••
{continued in the comments}
#metoo #itsneverokay #ibelieveyou #yourenotalone #nowimawarrior

#believewomen

it’s been 17 years since the last time i was sexually abused. yes the last time. it happened not once, not twice but, multiple times. i was 6 when it staed. it happened wherever my uncle could get me alone. family pay with too many people? let’s skip it today. babysitting me? perfect alone time! and it kept happening because i was too young to know that what was happening was wrong. and then after that when i did realize what was going on, i became strong and told him to fuck off. i felt shameful and held it in for years to come. 7 years to be exact. when i finally came out with it... no one believed me except my parents, brother, and grandma. i’ll have you know i have a large family. for that many people to not believe me broke me. how do you not believe someone??? how?? what did i have to lose except my entire family??? •••••
the worst was when we were on a family vacation to bethany beach and my family was upstairs playing cards and i had to use the bathroom but someone was upstairs. i went downstairs really fast and he trapped me in a bedroom on the lower floor. locked me in. i screamed. •••••
no one heard me. i cried. my dad asked why i was upset when i went back upstairs. i told him i fell. he asked to see my legs to check for bruising (i have anemia so ice is my best friend). no bruises. he didn’t question it. next day i wanted to go back to the house from the beach but it was a far walk so my parents didn’t want to bring me back so my uncle offered. i said no it’s okay i’m fine here and they were like you made a big fuss now go. what was i supposed to do? i went and when i was showering he entered the bathroom and well, i don’t even have to say what happened next because it’s not pretty. •••••
{continued in the comments}

text:
i spent the past week asking women from all over to tell me about a time when they felt unsafe.-
-

to fellow women these stories, while upsetting, are not surprising. -
-

we deal with problems like this on a daily basis. these stories are merely the ones that stick out to us the most. -
-

my hope is that by sharing these stories the men in our lives will understand the stress and anxiety of being a woman in todays society. -
-

to all the good men out there reading: it is not enough to simply be “good,” you have the power to influence your fellow man and help women feel safe. -
-

to all the women who contributed: thank you and i’m sorry. let’s keep fighting the good fight and one day we will take our runs back.-
-
-
-
#takeourrunsback #endviolenceagainstwomen #standtogether #empoweringwomen #timesup #metoo

text:
all of us have trauma. all genders. being alive is kind of traumatic. we have huge addiction issues here in the u.s. so that right there says it all. before i experienced the type of trauma that silenced and paralyzed me, i definitely said to myself 'well if that happened to me i would scream, i would fight, afterwards i would get help and turn him in.' (also once some of us get past the shock trauma state we do all these things and nothing comes of it except more humiliation.) this is a message for everyone who is saying things like, "you can’t stay in your victimhood forever..." please be careful telling us to not get too boisterous, or sulk in our victimhood too much.
when i read these well thought out posts and videos from women saying this, it makes me cringe; anything that feels like a “shush” to me (even if you think it’s for my own benefit) compounds my feeling of powerlessness. i need people to say, "tell me the story of what happened to you.” in my upcoming book i share a type of trauma that took everything from me. when women read it they say, you reminded me that what happened to me was really fucking terrible and i don’t have to pretend or lie to myself about it anymore. this is what dr. ford did for millions of women!

can you imagine us as soldiers coming home from a war? we are veterans of a battlefield where the masculine severely terrorized and harmed the feminine. the ongoing war fractured our sense of reality and safety. so can you invite us warriors/veterans into your hometown and ask us to speak about our war history so it can come into the light and be healed for us all? let’s honor our soldiers of war. this is the perspective i am asking you to take. can you? can you please for the sake of humanity treat us with kindness and trust that our healing process might be loud, it might be scary, it might be really uncomfortable to witness. and if you can’t witness then it’s okay to leave the room but don’t dictate or try to gauge my process. i am rebirthing equality. it did exist at one time, i’m asking us all to try and remember. 
#troublemaker 
#metoo
#feminist
#rebirthingequality
#reverendlilianabarzola
#retreatyourself 
#ibelieveher
