text:
“when you get to a place where you understand that love and belonging, your worthiness, is a birthright and not something you have to earn, anything is possible.” ~brene brown
.
.
such a honor to have visited two very warm yoga communities this weekend, and to have shared in cultivating a sense of empowerment and belonging. .
.
as we called in shakti, the divine feminine, and dedicated our practices to healing wounds both our own and that of the collective consciousness, i felt that together, we did something good for this country. which continues to need so much healing. 💚 i hope that christine blasey ford felt our energy, and i hope she heard my prayers. 🕊🙏🏻 my personal dedications this weekend were all for #her ⚓️
.
.
.
#metoo #yogaheals #havematwilltravel #travelingyogateacher #pranavinyasa #speakout #riseup #womenempowerment

durante 10 minutos, con sus pañuelos verdes toman la palabra contando los abusos de poder recibidos, los chistes misóginos que les hicieron, los comentarios diarios alrededor de la ropa con la que se vestían para cursar y también los casos de acoso sexual por parte de docentes, preceptores y autoridades que vivieron durante los cinco años de cursada.⠀

"no habernos escuchado fue una decisión política que hoy ya no pueden tomar. les arrebatamos este espacio para brindarles esas respuestas que van a marcar el camino a seguir a partir de ahora", agregaron. ⠀

“when i was 22, a successful screenwriter in his 50s read some of my writing and asked to discuss a future project. we began working on a screenplay collaboration, meeting sporadically. a few months and a lot of work in, i received an email with an attachment. it was a six-page document detailing the times he had masturbated before and after our meetings. he told me he was going to ‘have’ me. he said he had ‘had a lot of women’. he also referred to his wife as his ‘primary partner’ in an attempt to convince me. 
this was right before the #metoo movement blew up. i was devastated, embarrassed and powerless. when other women started to speak out publicly about harassment in the film industry, i felt such relief. their voices were being heard." — brooke ✏️

text:
💪🏻 as a woman i have found it hard to accept how society still treats us. visually i have seen how we have been demeaned, accosted, and devalued as individuals. i myself have experienced, witnessed and been the listening ear to friends, family, loved ones, and clients who have been assaulted, abused, and/ or violated by a predator. it’s hard to sit back and accept this anymore. these “stories” are real. they have caused damage mentally, physically and emotionally. a trust was broken and it hopes to repair but no one can tell you how to survive and gain that trust back. it can happen anywhere, everywhere and to anyone. it has happened to me; as a child, as an adult, as a student, as a hairdresser, as someone who thought it was love, and someone who didn’t want to accept love. they all have names and we all have secrets. but it doesn’t mean it isn’t true. 💪🏻•
•
•

text: we should start the month off by learning the proper way to support survivors of domestic violence. lesson number one: don’t ask a survivor why they didn’t “just leave.” in case you are too lazy to research the psychology behind this. i will give you my reasons in hopes that you will understand your friends and family better and maybe give you some terms to research so you can better support them. 1. he created a trauma bond. 2. he successfully isolated me from everyone and everything. 3. co-dependency as a result of toxic shame and isolation. 4. survival.  #domesticviolenceawareness #metoo #whyididntjustleave #stopvictimblaming #stopvictimshaming #domesticviolencesurvivor #octoberisdomesticviolenceawarenessmonth

text:
hi friends, it's been almost 1 year since i had an experience at a design conference with a man who i felt acted incredibly sexually inappropriately to me. it was coincidentally the same exact weekend that alyssa milano had tweeted using the #metoo hashtag and started the popularization of the movement. between both events, plus the events of last week, i've had a lot coming up - as many have. so i wrote this. and i recorded it. and i'm pretty terrified, but i think it's a step in the right direction in terms of telling my story and the change i'd like to see in not only the design industry, in every industry, and in every society. if you are not a designer or an illustrator, i believe this can be applied to almost any industry. but this piece is most specifically for anyone in the graphic design industry that’s ever been to an industry event or conference or had a job. i find that this behavior is much worse in nyc that it is in la, much worse. so i’m that’s interesting. full video & text in my bio. i’m terrified goodbye •
•
•
#sexualharassment #graphicdesign #story #storytelling #prose

text:
🍯 hello, honies. last week was heart-wrenching, uncomfortable, and hopefully transformational for all. i had to hide out a little, process, and listen.
🙏🏾i want to thank those women who have shared their stories here and on the national stage. we’re the better for your honesty and courage. my heart is with you.
🙏🏾i want to thank the men who have loved me - my dad, my brother, and those loves that came along when i was starting to despair.  i want to thank you for standing by us now, when we are cleansing away the countless shocks in a life lived as women - the aggressions and mini-aggressions that have weeded our lives, sometimes clogging our progress and clouding our sense of worth.
🙏🏾 i want to thank the men who are loving us now by honestly and truthfully apologizing for past actions. 🙏🏾 i want to thank those who are realizing that justice for all means just that - and that it is time at long, long last for those in power to perceive the world through a woman’s eyes - for all our sakes.

text:
non tudor post! i was in college during the whole lilith fair scene, and i sang my anger out at boys along with alanis morissette. a dear friend introduced me to the music of @toriamos and i immediately fell in love. everything about her was the opposite of what i expected a woman to be. the way she played the piano. the way she seriously did not give two f&cks what you thought about her. the way she openly talked about being raped in a way that took back her power, and the way she reclaimed her sexuality.

like a lot of women i know, i've been triggered by the recent supreme court hearings. it's like every experience that i chalked up to being a bad party, or just the way guys are is coming back to haunt me. then, as a young woman with an amazing career, living in london, los angeles, and manhattan, being mansplained basic functions of my job. being told i should smile more because it made people uncomfortable if i didn't. that i should paint my nails and wear heels. and more sinister close calls that made me question reality... had i really been acting like i wanted it? and even if i did, did that mean i wanted it with that person specifically? 
i'm grateful that i discovered the music of tori amos early on, and i could go back to little earthquakes and channel my anger through her. and now, i am glad that more women are getting angry.

i know some men are upset and hurt by this new power that is being unleashed by women and #metoo. good men, men who would never dream of hurting a woman, and feel as if the entire gender is being blamed for the actions of a few. and while that sucks, and i don't want any men to feel attacked for something they didn't do, the answer isn't for us to bottle back up our anger. it's for all of us to get equally angry, and for men to finally hold the anger that we've lived with forever.

my college boyfriend couldn't handle tori amos because of her anger. he even said as much. it made me love her more. and i left him. i think it's time for men to all embrace the parts of women that they haven't been able to hold before, including the anger and sadness. then we can all move forward together.
#ibelieveher #ibelievechristineblaseyford

a rede de televisão bbc mostra que esses sites não regulados de doação de esperma acabam sendo usados para constranger mulheres ou tentar convencê-las a praticar sexo sem proteção.

de acordo com nossa diretora dra silvana chedid: “as mulheres não devem de forma alguma recorrer a esses sites! além do risco de assédio há também o enorme risco de contrair doenças graves”. saiba mais sobre a investigação, link na bio

text:
how can we justify this brilliant story in the year of #metoo when victims of sexual predation are finally asserting control over their bodies, lives and futures? is humbert humbert an anachronistic figure or a current threat? is his wily intelligence worthy of respect or at least regard or is his exploitation so perverse and unacceptable that he has no place in any literary canon? and what about nabokov’s writing? his elegance and his wit? should we relegate it to a dark time, pre-enlightenment? won’t there always be deviants and their stories worth telling particularly by nabokov and dostoyevsky? or is lolita as much a glorification as an indictment? is it a valuable relic? what is your opinion?

text:
bij huiselijk geweld denken we vaak in eerste instantie aan fysiek geweld. daar heb ik weinig mee te maken gehad: één keer werd ik tegen m’n heup geschopt door een ex, één keer lag ik na één slag op m’n kaak ineens op de keukenvloer door een andere ex. ik vond beide keren dat het m’n eigen schuld was. persoonlijk had ik meer te maken met seksueel geweld; misbruik, verkrachting, en met manipulatie. tien jaar geleden werkte ik bij het blijf van mijn lijf huis. de verhalen die ik daar hoorde, komen nog naar boven in mijn dromen. de vrouwen die op hun hoede zijn tot hun tweede natuur hebben gemaakt. de vele fietsen voor de deur met kinderzitjes illustreren de lieve gezichtjes die o zo vaak veel te stil of veel te baldadig waren. die van de ene op de andere dag waren opgepakt en hun bed, speelgoed, vriendjes en vriendinnetjes, klas, juffrouw en de speeltuin op de hoek van de straat hadden moeten achterlaten. als plantjes uit de aarde getrokken om ergens anders weer te worden geplant. wat vertel je de eerste dag op de school vlakbij het blijf van mijn lijfhuis over wie je bent en waarom je ineens daar in de klas zit? dit was niet de enige plaats. huiselijk geweld was aanwezig in de levens van vrouwen, jongeren en mannen die ik begeleidde in de verslavingszorg, in de crisisopvang en op de middelbare scholen waar ik  maatschappelijk werkster was. het was ook present bij de vrouwenvereniging waar ik vrijwilliger was, in de moskee en in mijn eigen straat. hier geldt hetzelfde als bij #metoo; iedereen zal zeggen dat huiselijk geweld verwerpelijk is, maar als het over je broer, je dochter, je gemeentelid, je beste vriend gaat; wat doe je dan? daders zijn niet altijd monsters, maar mensen met schulden, verslavings- en psychische problemen. we doen altijd zo blasé over alcohol, maar het percentage huiselijk geweld en kindermishandeling wat onder invloed van alcohol gebeurd is schrikbarend. en àls je er een gesprek over hebt; hoe verder? het komt voort uit patronen die mannen en vrouwen vanaf hun vroegste jeugd hebben gevormd. verbreek de cirkel voor het te laat is. zoek hulp.
#femaleblackout #huiselijkgeweld #schrijversvaninstagram

dit niet de enige plaats . huiselijk geweld aanwezig de levens van vrouwen , jongeren en mannen die ik begeleidde de verslavingszorg , de crisisopvang en op de middelbare scholen waar ik maatschappelijk werkster . het ook present bij de vrouwenvereniging waar ik vrijwilliger , de moskee en mijn eigen straat . hier geldt hetzelfde als bij iedereen zal zeggen dat huiselijk geweld verwerpelijk , maar als het je broer , je dochter , je gemeentelid , je beste vriend gaat ; wat doe je dan ? daders zijn niet altijd monsters , maar mensen met schulden , verslavings- en psychische problemen . doen altijd zo blasé alcohol , maar het percentage huiselijk geweld en kindermishandeling wat onder invloed van alcohol gebeurd schrikbarend . en àls je er een gesprek hebt ; hoe verder ? text: a new month has began , the moonlight season has ended ...taking some time to reflect and learn from a few things.. i’ve noticed my survival tactics were fairly high during the season not just at work but in personal life. growing up in the system and on the streets with no real person to call mom, or a dad. no family to lift me up, barely attached myself to “friends” was difficult , i’m very cautious about who i allow in my life and i’m learning to adjust and just let people in. but it’s hard, this month i’m focusing on myself , unlearning the abuse that put me in such a frail way. i have hopes to maybe share my story , to maybe help others but more so help myself release some of this pent of feeling i have. i have kept a very tight lid on my past, it’s a , ugly , cringe worthy story with hints of some brightness... but maybe i can bring awareness to unspoken issues #survivor#fosteryouth#shepercisted#endtrafficking#endtheabuse#sharkbaitsjourney#brokenbutstrong#istillcryanditsok#metoo

text: #metoo
name: Heidi Adams
tweet_full: #metoo

text:
we hear all the time about the “me too” movement.  honestly, more and more cases are coming out especially those that are sexual harassment situations.  as the director of the nb cpa, this post is to bring awareness to individuals (male or female) that this is happening to in our industry and it’s completely unacceptable.  never let fear

allow you to be victimized by this epidemic.  this is not ok.  my door is always open, so if you have any issues or problems understanding what sexual harassment is; please read below for the associated behaviors.  i am always here to listen and be a support to anyone who needs help. 
types of verbal behavior that might constitute sexual harassment are: •continuous idle chatter of a sexual nature and graphic sexual descriptions; •sexual slurs, sexual innuendoes and other comments about a person’s clothing, body and/or sexual activities; •offensive and persistent risqué jokes or jesting and kidding about sex or gender-specific traits; •suggestive or insulting sounds such as whistling, wolf calls or kissing sounds; •sexually provocative comments or compliments about a person’s clothing or the way their clothes fit; •comments of a sexual nature about weight, body shape, size or figure; •comments about the sensuality of a person, or his/her spouse or significant other; •distribution of written or graphic materials that are derogatory and are of a sexual nature; •repeated unsolicited propositions for dates and/or sexual relations; •asking about sexual fantasies, preferences or history.  types of gestures or non-verbal behaviors that might be considered sexual harassment are: •sexual looks such as leering and ogling with suggestive overtones; •licking lips or teeth, winking or throwing kisses; •holding or eating food provocatively; •lewd gestures, such as hand or sign language to denote sexual activity; •persistent and unwelcome flirting; •staring at an individual or looking a person up and down (elevator eyes); •displaying sexually suggestive pictures, calendars, posters, statues, etc.

people please, do not allow yourself to be a victim, we have zero tolerance for these behaviors. #metoo #zerotolerance

text:
one of the many reasons i will never regret my tattoo: seeing someone who assaulted me make fun of women who report, on social media. i’m not ashamed of myself for what you did, i’m disappointed in myself for what i didn’t do so that you could be held accountable for your actions. i wasn’t strong enough to confront you then, but just like this tattoo, i will live the rest of my life with what you did to me. 
and if it inspires even just one person to be brave enough to come forward, get out of a bad situation, pick themselves back up, or help others, it’s all worth it.

text:
#diedamezupferd || milla jovovich in “the messenger” as jeanne d’arc
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
the french heroine was said to have heard revelations from god and saints as a young adult. those voices instructed her to support charles vii and help him fight the english in 1428, who besieged orléans. after driving out the invading troops as a part of the cavalry and leading charles to his crowning in reims to become king of france, jeanne got captured in a battle against the burgundians and handed over to the english. she got condemned as a witch and heretic and finally burned at the stake in 1431. in 1920 pope benedict xv canonized her as a catholic saint.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
jeanne d’arc became a popular figure and has inspired various cultural works since the time of her death. shakespeare, schiller, voltaire or brecht dealt with her legacy in written form and partially brought it to the stage. she can be found in the work of rossini, verdi, tchaikovsky or bernstein, cohen and patti smith, was painted by rubens, lynch, la fresnaye and many more and was played by ingrid bergman, renée falconetti, jean seberg, and tilda swinton. she’s a symbol of ravenous stamina, a lgbt icon because of gender fluidity and keeps inspiring in the era of the #metoo-movement.
